Hi $name! As a librarian and a rock climber and Wikipedia editor in your free time, you've gotten used to being around books all the time. But you never imagined that you would end up in the middle of one of those very fictional worlds. 

It all started a few hours ago. You were putting books away when suddenly...

[[one fell on you.]]
[[you picked up an interesting one to read.]]
[[you see a light emitting from one of the books on the shelf and pick it up.]]

<a title="Ralf Roletschek, CC BY 3.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg"><img width="960" alt="Science library of Upper Lusatia in Görlitz, Germany." src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg/960px-13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg"></a>


:: Cinderella {"position":"850,650","size":"100,100"}
You feel a jolt in your body as you feel yourself teleported from the forest. When you come to, you're in the bushes next to the most elaborate staircase that you've ever seen, as people wearing fancy clothes climb up the stairs. 

You sigh. You're in the middle of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinderella">//Cinderella//</a>.

<a title="Thomas Wolf, www.foto-tw.de, CC BY-SA 3.0 DE &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/de/deed.en&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Neues_Rathaus_Hannover_2013.jpg"><img width="960" alt="Neues Rathaus Hannover 2013" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Neues_Rathaus_Hannover_2013.jpg/960px-Neues_Rathaus_Hannover_2013.jpg"></a>


:: Climb the castle with your rock climbing skills. {"position":"750,1675","size":"100,100"}
You roll up your sleeves. It's time to put your rock climbing skills to the test. 

This castle isn't any harder than anything that you've climbed before, and it doesn't take long before you discover the room with a bunch of mattresses. 

You let yourself in through the open window and immediately see the bed with the pile of mattresses, where you see a light shine through. How are you supposed to get the pea from underneath?

Just then, the prince barges through the door.

"What are you doing here?" he asks. 

So much for inconspiculously climbing up. 

He looks over at the mattresses and suddenly grows excited. "Did you feel the pea underneath?"

[[Yes.]]
[[No.]]

<a title="Eliedion, CC BY-SA 4.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG"><img width="960" alt="Efteling AntonPieckplein - Efteling museum - de prinses op de erwt" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG/960px-Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG"></a>


:: End {"position":"675,1950","size":"100,100"}
When you next wake up, you're laying on the floor of the fairy tale section, with the four books you had stepped into splayed on the ground around you. 

You pick up <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Princess_and_the_Pea">//The Princess and the Pea//</a>, and are surprised to see that your adventure made no impact on the story. You check the other three books for changes as well, and don't see any. 

Maybe you could've had more fun, if you dared to.

Sam, another librarian, comes over.

"What are you doing over there?" they ask. They look to the other side of you. "Oh, are these the items we'll be showcasing for Fairy Tales week next week?"

Turning around, you see a pile of the items that you had to touch to get back. 

1. First is the poisoined apple, which just looks like a regular apple here (maybe nobody should eat it though). 
2. Next is Cinderella's gold shoes.
3. Then there's the silver shoes.
4. Finally, it's the one singular pea from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Princess_and_the_Pea">//The Princess and the Pea//</a>.

"Although I don't know if the apple and the pea would be engaging... maybe you could go and get some more interesting items like the shoes?"

"Nope." You stand up. "It's your turn. I'm pretty tired just finding all of this stuff."

"Weren't you just napping..." Sam trails off, but then shakes their head. "Just come over to the circulation desk, we have a fifth-grade class coming soon."

You grab the four books, and while you put <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snow-White">//Snow White//</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinderella">//Cinderella//</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Princess_and_the_Pea">//The Princess and the Pea//</a> in the fairy tale section, you take <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wonderful_Wizard_of_Oz">//The Wonderful Wizard of Oz//</a> with you, putting it in the 20th century children's fiction section as you head back to the circulation desk.

Sitting down, you look around at the library. You viewed your mundane life as boring before, but maybe you're wrong.

Maybe there's a little bit of magic left in it after all. 

[[Turn the page ->The End]]

<a title="Ralf Roletschek, CC BY 3.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg"><img width="960" alt="Science library of Upper Lusatia in Görlitz, Germany." src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg/960px-13-11-02-olb-by-RalfR-03.jpg"></a>


:: Follow the Light {"position":"575,500","size":"100,100"}
Outside of the dwarves' house, you see the old farmer's wife standing there with her basket. Of course, you know that's actually the evil queen in disguise. Her basket is glowing, which is where you presume she's kept the poisoned apple. 

She reaches in and grabs the apple, readying herself to knock on the door. Does she not see it's glowing?

What should you do?

[[Touch the apple.]]
[[Stay still.]]
[[Say hi to the evil queen.]]

<a title="MCAD Library, CC BY 2.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Snow_White_and_the_Seven_Dwarfs_-_53078643357_-_Jack_Zipes_Historic_Fairy_Tale_Postcard_Collection_-_Kubel,_Otto_(German,_1868-1951).jpg"><img width="500" alt="Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs - 53078643357 - Jack Zipes Historic Fairy Tale Postcard Collection - Kubel, Otto (German, 1868-1951)" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Snow_White_and_the_Seven_Dwarfs_-_53078643357_-_Jack_Zipes_Historic_Fairy_Tale_Postcard_Collection_-_Kubel%2C_Otto_%28German%2C_1868-1951%29.jpg/500px-Snow_White_and_the_Seven_Dwarfs_-_53078643357_-_Jack_Zipes_Historic_Fairy_Tale_Postcard_Collection_-_Kubel%2C_Otto_%28German%2C_1868-1951%29.jpg"></a>


:: Interact with Dorothy {"position":"425,1550","size":"100,100"}
With your time spent in all of these stories, you've grown a little bolder about interacting with these story characters. You walk up to the house, where Dorothy looks shocked.

"What are you doing here?"

"I'm trying to get home too," you say. "Sorry Dorothy; I wish I could help you."

This is something that definetly needs to be done, and there's absolutely no getting around it. 

You reach down and touch the witch's shoes. You quickly find yourself enveloped, once again, within the blinding yellow light.

<a title="N509FZ, CC BY-SA 4.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Silver_high-heeled_shoes_on_legs_(20230417104455).jpg"><img width="960" alt="Silver high-heeled shoes on legs (20230417104455)" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Silver_high-heeled_shoes_on_legs_%2820230417104455%29.jpg/960px-Silver_high-heeled_shoes_on_legs_%2820230417104455%29.jpg"></a>

(link: "What happens?")[
When you wake up, you find yourself by the side of a castle on a rainy night. You don't immediately know which story this is in reference to, as there are a lot of fairy tales (or even other books) that have a castle. 

Then you remember the book that was on the shelf right next to the others: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Princess_and_the_Pea">//The Princess and the Pea
//</a> 

You look up at the castle. The most iconic object from this story is the pea though, located under all of those mattresses. There's no way you could be able to go in and touch it inconspiciously. 

Additionally, with the time you spend in each story slowly decreasing, there's no way that you'll be able to get in before the actual princess of the story arrives.

[[Climb the castle with your rock climbing skills.]]
[[Knock on the front door.]]

<a title="Franz Scheyerer, Public domain, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg"><img width="960" alt="Franz Scheyerer - Das alte Schloß Rain" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg/960px-Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg"></a>
]


:: Knock on the front door. {"position":"450,1675","size":"100,100"}
Despite being nervous, you go to the front door and knock. What would be the alternative?

The prince of the story opens the door and looks down at you. 

"Can I help you?" he asks.

"Can I have a place to stay? It's really rainy."

The prince looks skeptical at first, but eventually widens the door and lets you in. 

You're led up a long spiral staircase, to a big room at the end of the hall.

"You can stay there. Let me know if you need anything." The prince leaves.

Peering into the room, you see that it's the right room with the large pile of mattresses.

But you're not sure how much time you have left. Can you really stay until tomorrow morning? 

You climb up the ladder at the side of the bed. Maybe if you pretend to sleep and then call the prince, you can leave tonight. You can't even feel the pea under all of these mattresses, so you'll probably have to lie. 

After five minutes, you call the prince back.

"This bed is uncomfortable; I can't sleep." You can't begin to grapple with the rudeness of saying that to a host who has offered you a place to stay, but this is the only way.

The prince looks over at the bed. "Did you feel the pea underneath?"

He looks over at the mattresses and suddenly grows excited. "Did you feel the pea underneath?"

[[Yes.]]
[[No]]

<a title="Eliedion, CC BY-SA 4.0 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG"><img width="960" alt="Efteling AntonPieckplein - Efteling museum - de prinses op de erwt" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG/960px-Efteling_AntonPieckplein_-_Efteling_museum_-_de_prinses_op_de_erwt.JPG"></a>


:: No {"position":"500,1850","size":"100,100"}
"No, I didn't feel it," you admit.

"Okay, then why did you call me?" he asked.

"I heard a myth that you had a pea underneath all of these mattresses to test for princesses. I wanted to ask if that was true. You just told me, so I guess that defeats the purpose of the test."

"Okay, know-it-all." You find it odd that most of the characters that you've interacted with use modern day slang, but you brush it off.

The doorbell rings, and the prince turns away. "I'm going to have to ask you to leave now. Hopefully whoever is at the door is a //real// princess."  

As you descend down the steps and are led out the back door, you sigh, looking up at the sky, where the rain still hasn't let up. Do you have no way of getting home now?

Maybe you should've chosen otherwise?

[[Knock on the front door.]]

<a title="Franz Scheyerer, Public domain, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg"><img width="960" alt="Franz Scheyerer - Das alte Schloß Rain" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg/960px-Franz_Scheyerer_-_Das_alte_Schlo%C3%9F_Rain.jpg"></a>


:: No. {"position":"800,1800","size":"100,100"}
"No, I didn't feel it," you admit.

"Okay, so you just broke into this castle then? I don't remember inviting you in."

The prince is okay with break-ins, but only if you're a princess, you suppose. The wrong conclusion to draw from this interaction, but it seems to be true. 

"I heard a myth that you had a pea underneath all of these mattresses to test for princesses. I wanted to ask if that was true. You just told me, so I guess that defeats the purpose of the test."

"Okay, know-it-all." You find it odd that most of the characters that you've interacted with use modern day slang, but you brush it off. 

The doorbell rings, and the prince turns away. "I'm going to have to ask you to leave now. Hopefully whoever is at the door is a //real// princess."

As you descend down the steps and are led out the back door, you sigh. Do you have no way of getting home now?

Maybe you should've chosen otherwise?

